<p><a href="https://www.pinkvilla.com/entertainment/updates/heres-why-neil-nitin-mukesh-thinks-toxic-bollywood-enjoys-someones-failure-1387157">Neil Nitin Mukesh</a> shared that he personally designed the interiors of his home. The day of the housewarming was also the day of his Roka ceremony, when his wife Rukmini entered the house for the first time. Later, during the COVID-19 lockdown, the couple spent special moments there with their daughter, Nurvi.</p>

<p>The house was originally designed as a bachelor pad, featuring unique materials like brick walls, cement finishes&nbsp;and battlet onyx. &ldquo;There&rsquo;s no paint on the walls,&rdquo; Neil said. &ldquo;We live near the sea, and I wanted to avoid dampness.&rdquo;</p>

<p><strong>Artistic touches and vaastu-approved d&eacute;cor</strong></p>

<p>Neil&rsquo;s love for art is evident in every corner. His living room features a console designed by Pinakin and two artworks by his friend Niyati Kanakia. &ldquo;This is my favourite artwork,&rdquo; he said, pointing to one piece made entirely from magazine paper.</p>

<p>He also highlighted a stunning African Tiger Onyx wall, imported from Africa and installed by Elegant Marble. &ldquo;This direction was coming as Agni, so I got the idea to clad that wall,&rdquo; Neil explained.</p>

<p>In his bedroom, Neil opted for cozy tones with a hotel-like feel. The door frames are made of marble, and the guest room, once a TV room, has a travertine marble wall and a sleek lacquer-polished table.</p>

<p>From spirituality to design, Neil Nitin Mukesh&rsquo;s house reflects his artistic side, deep beliefs, and cherished memories, making it truly one-of-a-kind.</p>
